---
import IncidentLayout from '../../../layouts/IncidentLayout.astro';
import IncidentHero from '../../../components/IncidentHero.astro';
import QuickFacts from '../../../components/QuickFacts.astro';
import TimelineEvent from '../../../components/TimelineEvent.astro';
import SourceList from '../../../components/SourceList.astro';
import TransmissionTower from '../../../components/illustrations/TransmissionTower';
import SACascadeMap from '../../../components/SACascadeMap';
import FullscreenWrapper from '../../../components/FullscreenWrapper';
---

<IncidentLayout title="South Australia Statewide Blackout" description="September 2016: Twin tornadoes and a hidden wind farm vulnerability combined to black out an entire state in 87 seconds.">

<IncidentHero
  title="South Australia Statewide Blackout"
  date="September 28, 2016"
  location="South Australia (entire state)"
  keyStat="87 sec"
  keyStatLabel="to total blackout"
  severity="blackout"
/>

<QuickFacts facts={[
  { value: "1.7M", label: "People affected (entire state)" },
  { value: "456 MW", label: "Wind generation lost in 7 seconds" },
  { value: "850 MW", label: "Interconnector overload (650 MW rated)" },
  { value: "22", label: "Transmission towers destroyed" },
  { value: "13 days", label: "Full restoration time" },
  { value: "A$367M", label: "Estimated economic cost" },
]} />

<h2>What Happened</h2>

<div class="float-right ml-6 mb-4" style="width: 160px;">
  <TransmissionTower client:visible width={160} height={100} />
</div>

<p>
  A once-in-50-year storm swept across South Australia with twin tornadoes packing winds up to 260 km/h. The tornadoes ripped through transmission corridors, destroying 22 high-voltage towers and severing the lines connecting the state's northern wind farms to Adelaide. <a href="#sa-timeline" class="font-mono text-xs" style="color: var(--color-primary); opacity: 0.7;">(continue below)</a>
</p>

<div class="my-8 rounded-lg overflow-hidden" style="background: var(--color-bg-alt); border: 1px solid var(--color-surface-light); padding: 16px;">
  <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: space-between; margin-bottom: 12px;">
    <div class="font-mono text-sm font-semibold tracking-wide uppercase" style="color: var(--color-text);">SA Grid — September 28, 2016</div>
    <span class="font-mono text-xs" style="color: var(--color-primary); opacity: 0.7; border: 1px solid rgba(34,211,238,0.2); padding: 1px 8px; border-radius: 3px; cursor: pointer;" onclick="this.closest('div').querySelector('button')?.click()">Interactive</span>
  </div>
  <FullscreenWrapper client:visible label="Fullscreen">
    <SACascadeMap client:visible height={400} />
  </FullscreenWrapper>
</div>

<p>
  As transmission lines fell, voltage dips rippled through the grid. Wind turbines are designed to ride through brief voltage drops, but each turbine has a safety limit on how many dips it can handle in quick succession. Nine wind farms hit that limit almost simultaneously, dropping 456 MW of generation in under 7 seconds.
</p>

<p id="sa-timeline">
  The single interconnector to Victoria tried to compensate, surging to 850 MW against its 650 MW capacity. It tripped on overload protection, isolating the entire state. Within seconds, every remaining generator shut down. Total <a href="/research/topics/cascading-failures">cascading failure</a>.
</p>

<h2>Timeline</h2>

<TimelineEvent
  time="16:16:49"
  title="First fault: 66 kV line near Adelaide trips"
  description="A distribution line trips from storm damage but automatically resets. The cascade sequence has begun."
  severity="warning"
/>

<TimelineEvent
  time="16:17:36"
  title="First major 275 kV line destroyed"
  description="The Brinkworth-Templers West line faults as tornado damage near Blyth takes out transmission towers. Power flow begins redistributing."
  severity="critical"
/>

<TimelineEvent
  time="16:17:55"
  title="Wind farms begin mass disconnection"
  description="Repeated voltage dips exceed the ride-through limits on wind turbine protection systems. Multiple farms start shedding output simultaneously."
  severity="critical"
/>

<TimelineEvent
  time="16:18:09"
  title="456 MW lost in 7 seconds"
  description="Hallett drops 123 MW, Hornsdale drops 86 MW, Snowtown drops 106 MW. Nine wind farms lose output almost simultaneously. The grid cannot absorb this."
  severity="collapse"
/>

<TimelineEvent
  time="16:18:14"
  title="Heywood interconnector overloads"
  description="The sole link to Victoria surges to 850 MW trying to compensate, far exceeding its 650 MW capacity. Both circuits trip on overload protection."
  severity="collapse"
/>

<TimelineEvent
  time="16:18:16"
  title="System Black"
  description="South Australia is completely isolated from the National Electricity Market. Remaining generators trip on under-frequency protection. The entire state goes dark."
  severity="collapse"
/>

<TimelineEvent
  time="19:00"
  title="First customers restored"
  description="After a complex black-start process requiring power from Victoria, first Adelaide metro customers get power back. Full restoration takes 13 days."
  severity="normal"
/>

<h2>Root Cause</h2>

<div class="my-8 p-6 rounded-xl" style="background: var(--color-bg-alt); border-left: 4px solid var(--color-danger);">
  <div class="font-mono text-xs font-semibold mb-3" style="color: var(--color-danger); letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase;">The Hidden Vulnerability</div>
  <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3" style="color: var(--color-text-muted);">
    Wind turbines have a safety feature called "repeat-LVRT protection" that disconnects them after too many voltage dips in a short window. The critical finding: <strong style="color: var(--color-text);">these protection settings were invisible to the grid operator.</strong> AEMO had no idea nine wind farms would disconnect simultaneously.
  </p>
  <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-0" style="color: var(--color-text-muted);">
    The OEM default settings on the turbines created a systemic risk that no one could see in the grid models. When the storm caused rapid voltage dips, the protection triggered across multiple farms at once, removing 456 MW in seconds.
  </p>
</div>

<h2>Could This Have Been Prevented?</h2>

<div class="my-8 p-6 rounded-xl" style="background: rgba(16, 185, 129, 0.06); border-left: 4px solid var(--color-success);">
  <div class="font-mono text-xs font-semibold mb-3" style="color: var(--color-success); letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase;">VPP Prevention Case</div>
  <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3" style="color: var(--color-text-muted);">
    This blackout directly led to the construction of the <a href="/research/incidents/2017-hornsdale-battery-response">Hornsdale Power Reserve</a> (Tesla Big Battery). A fleet of distributed batteries could have absorbed the 456 MW shortfall in milliseconds, buying time for operators to manage the interconnector load.
  </p>
  <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-0" style="color: var(--color-text-muted);">
    At the time, South Australia had zero utility-scale battery storage. Eighteen months later, the <a href="/research/incidents/2017-hornsdale-battery-response">Hornsdale battery</a> would prove that 100 MW of fast-acting storage could prevent exactly this type of cascade.
  </p>
</div>

